00:03:22.920 --> 00:03:26.730
Antarctic Lakes
The continent of Antarctica is so inhospitable

00:03:26.730 --> 00:03:31.240
and cold that everyone thought the whole place
was just frozen ice.

00:03:31.240 --> 00:03:35.140
Then a man named Jonathan Kingslake came along
and changed everything.

00:03:35.140 --> 00:03:37.630
I know, perfect name right??

00:03:37.630 --> 00:03:43.130
In 2010, he was observing a picture from Google
Earth of the Nielsen Ice Shelf in Antarctica.

00:03:43.130 --> 00:03:47.100
When he did, he noticed that there were water
channels that could clearly be seen from the

00:03:47.100 --> 00:03:51.470
sky, channels that would only exist if there
was a lake nearby.

00:03:51.470 --> 00:03:55.870
The idea of such a "drainage system" in Antarctica
was long thought of as impossible because

00:03:55.870 --> 00:03:59.790
of the cold temperatures, but Kingslake’s
discovery prompted a more rigorous search

00:03:59.790 --> 00:04:04.690
of Antarctica, and researchers found around
700 different drainage systems throughout

00:04:04.690 --> 00:04:08.570
the continent, each of them feeding a lake
in one form or another.

00:04:08.570 --> 00:04:13.860
Some of the water even traveled 75 miles in
order to reach its final destination.

00:04:13.860 --> 00:04:20.070
Recent inventories have identified 379 lakes
in Antarctica, and we will probably find more.

00:04:20.070 --> 00:04:25.220
Now we know that Antarctica has many subglacial
lakes, covered by several kilometers of ice.

00:04:25.220 --> 00:04:29.310
Many of them are connected and water flows
from lake to lake.

00:04:29.310 --> 00:04:33.511
Finding these systems and lakes has changed
not only how we look at Antarctica, but how

00:04:33.511 --> 00:04:36.040
we see the oceans as a whole.

00:04:36.040 --> 00:04:37.100
5.

00:04:37.100 --> 00:04:40.470
Rivers of London
Did you know that under the streets of London

00:04:40.470 --> 00:04:42.220
there were rivers and canals?

00:04:42.220 --> 00:04:47.900
In 1827, London wasn't nearly the size it
was now, and instead of Pancras and Euston

00:04:47.900 --> 00:04:51.780
Road, there used to be a field where a river
once ran through.

00:04:51.780 --> 00:04:56.070
Fast forward to today, and those streets are
made of concrete and stone, but the river

00:04:56.070 --> 00:04:59.190
is still there, it's just underground.

00:04:59.190 --> 00:05:02.790
Alongside many other rivers that once went
through the London area.

00:05:02.790 --> 00:05:06.910
Alex Werner, head of history collections at
the Museum of London says that "Wherever you

00:05:06.910 --> 00:05:11.270
live, not far from your doorstep, you can
probably track down a hidden river you never

00:05:11.270 --> 00:05:13.160
would have guessed would be there!

00:05:13.160 --> 00:05:17.200
This particular river, called The River Fleet,
is one of many rivers that were eventually

00:05:17.200 --> 00:05:19.730
"buried" because of the expansion of London.

00:05:19.730 --> 00:05:23.240
And while you can go and find these rivers
yourself, you would have to know where to

00:05:23.240 --> 00:05:26.690
look, and many people in London right now
have no clue!!

00:05:26.690 --> 00:05:30.760
You can see a little piece of it above ground
as it flows under an arched bridge from Hampstead

00:05:30.760 --> 00:05:33.010
to Highgate Ponds in north London.

00:05:33.010 --> 00:05:36.870
The reason for this is that just like the
city, the rivers of the area have gone through

00:05:36.870 --> 00:05:41.000
many phases, including how the people of London
used them.

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:44.860
In the past they were used for drinking and
fishing, but over the centuries, the need

00:05:44.860 --> 00:05:47.330
for space was more important than the need
for water.

00:05:47.330 --> 00:05:52.360
Some of the areas around the hidden rivers
became harder to maintain, so it was decided

00:05:52.360 --> 00:05:55.900
to dam them up and use the land for the growing
population.

00:05:55.900 --> 00:05:59.820
Some are actually attempting to bring the
rivers back to the true surface, but efforts

00:05:59.820 --> 00:06:01.290
are very slow.

00:06:01.290 --> 00:06:04.740
Most of them are now sewers surrounded by
victorian brickwork.

00:06:04.740 --> 00:06:09.340
Other rivers that can be found underneath
London include: The Tyburn, The Walbrook,

00:06:09.340 --> 00:06:10.980
The Westbourne, and the Effra.

00:06:10.980 --> 00:06:11.980
4.

00:06:11.980 --> 00:06:15.160
Greenland Rivers
The Nation of Greenland is the largest island

00:06:15.160 --> 00:06:16.160
in the world.

00:06:16.160 --> 00:06:21.320
3/4ths of its surface mass is covered in ice,
however, underneath that sheet of ice and

00:06:21.320 --> 00:06:26.250
glaciers, scientists found a network of rivers
frozen in time.

00:06:26.250 --> 00:06:30.830
This river network is remarkably large, and
actually goes through much of Greenland proper,

00:06:30.830 --> 00:06:34.320
located underneath the Jakob-shavn Is-brae
glacier.

00:06:34.320 --> 00:06:38.639
It's also said that these rivers actually
have helped shape and maintain this glacier

00:06:38.639 --> 00:06:39.760
over time.

00:06:39.760 --> 00:06:43.960
Michael Cooper from the University of Bristol
in the United Kingdom, told Live Science in

00:06:43.960 --> 00:06:47.770
an interview that the channels seem to be
instrumental in controlling the location and

00:06:47.770 --> 00:06:50.210
form of the ice stream of the glacier.

00:06:50.210 --> 00:06:53.270
Without these channels, the glacier might
not even exist!

00:06:53.270 --> 00:06:55.110
Or be in the same place!!

00:06:55.110 --> 00:06:59.740
The Jakobshavn Isbrae glacier is actually
the world’s fastest glacier, moving towards

00:06:59.740 --> 00:07:02.770
the ocean at a rate of 11 miles per year.

00:07:02.770 --> 00:07:07.810
Further study proved that underneath the glacier
is a massive area of canyons, as well as ravines

00:07:07.810 --> 00:07:08.810
and streams.

00:07:08.810 --> 00:07:11.340
It’s another secret world on Earth!!

00:07:11.340 --> 00:07:15.690
Though many of the rivers that are under the
glacier aren't "alive" anymore, some of them

00:07:15.690 --> 00:07:17.340
are still going.

00:07:17.340 --> 00:07:18.560
3.

00:07:18.560 --> 00:07:22.420
Secret Rivers of Estonia
Legends and stories about Estonia’s secret

00:07:22.420 --> 00:07:24.970
rivers have been around for centuries.

00:07:24.970 --> 00:07:29.190
Animals and sometimes even people, would be
carried underground by the streams.

00:07:29.190 --> 00:07:34.919
Estonia is a country in Northern Europe that
borders the Baltic Sea and includes over 1,500

00:07:34.919 --> 00:07:36.130
islands.

00:07:36.130 --> 00:07:41.710
With thousands of lakes, the water of Estonia
is considered its most valuable natural resource.

00:07:41.710 --> 00:07:45.389
Researchers from Tallinn University say that
the secret rivers are true and that there

00:07:45.389 --> 00:07:48.800
are probably hundreds of them beneath the
surface of the country.

00:07:48.800 --> 00:07:49.800
How is that possible?

00:07:49.800 --> 00:07:53.750
Part of the reason is because nearly half
of the mainland is covered with carbonate

00:07:53.750 --> 00:07:55.670
rock such as limestone.

00:07:55.670 --> 00:08:00.139
Over time the land has been "karsted", or
eroded, making it easy for water to create

00:08:00.139 --> 00:08:02.139
fissures and sinkholes.

00:08:02.139 --> 00:08:06.340
This in turn both hid and created many of
the secret rivers in the area.

00:08:06.340 --> 00:08:11.370
Ones that were on the surface would fall into
sinkholes, and then start flowing underwater.

00:08:11.370 --> 00:08:15.400
After further study, The Estonian Book of
Wilderness lists 40 secret rivers with their

00:08:15.400 --> 00:08:20.010
starting and ending point, so in case your
cows disappear, you can try to find them before

00:08:20.010 --> 00:08:21.669
they get swept away!

00:08:21.669 --> 00:08:22.669
